Hardware Delivery Process – Functional Summary

Overview

This workflow manages hardware delivery operations performed at Le Comptoir.

It supports two different contexts:

* Users supported by the Group Catalog
* Users not supported by the Group Catalog

The process also supports replacement scenarios, where existing hardware must be returned before the new equipment is delivered.

The objective is to ensure:

* End-to-end traceability
* Standardized technician workflows
* Proper linkage between delivery and return operations
* Flexibility when exceptions occur
* Auditability of all actions performed

⸻

1. User Identification

The workflow always starts with the identification of the visitor.

Depending on the user profile, the system determines whether the user is supported by the Group Catalog or not.

This decision drives the workflow branch that will be used.

⸻

2. User Supported by Group Catalog (2B)

Request Identification

When the user is catalog-supported:

* the system displays all identified requests associated with the user.

If no request is available:

* the process ends immediately.

The technician selects the request to process.

⸻

Replacement Handling

The system checks whether the selected request is a replacement request.

If the request is NOT a replacement

The workflow continues directly to the new hardware delivery process.

If the request IS a replacement

The hardware return workflow must be executed first.

⸻

3. Replacement Return Workflow

Missing Hardware Check

The system checks whether the hardware that should be returned is available.

If the hardware is available

The technician proceeds with the return process.

The system checks whether the returned hardware is managed in HAM.

If the hardware is managed in HAM

The technician:

* scans or searches the equipment in HAM
* retrieves equipment information automatically

If the equipment cannot be identified:

* the technician manually enters the equipment information.

If the hardware is NOT managed in HAM

The technician manually enters the available equipment information.

Once completed:

* the returned hardware is added to the bucket
* the return operation is associated with the current request

⸻

Missing Hardware Exception

If the hardware to return is missing:

* the technician may decide whether or not to continue the process.

If the technician refuses to continue

The process ends and the request is not completed.

If the technician decides to continue anyway

The technician must:

* click “Skip return”
* enter a mandatory justification

The system then:

* logs the incomplete return
* associates the justification with the current request

This guarantees operational flexibility while preserving auditability.

⸻

4. New Hardware Delivery Workflow

Once the return workflow is completed (or bypassed), the technician starts the new hardware delivery workflow.

The system checks whether the delivered hardware is managed in HAM.

If the hardware is managed in HAM

The technician:

* scans or searches the equipment in HAM
* retrieves hardware information automatically

If the hardware cannot be identified:

* the technician manually enters the equipment information.

If the hardware is NOT managed in HAM

The technician manually enters the hardware information directly.

Once completed:

* the delivered item is added to the bucket

⸻

5. User Not Supported by Group Catalog (2A)

For users outside the Group Catalog:

* the technician manually selects the delivery type
* the technician enters the business request reference

The system then asks whether the operation is a replacement requiring hardware collection.

⸻

Replacement Scenario

If replacement hardware must be collected:

* the return workflow is executed first
* the same return rules and exception handling apply

This includes:

* HAM lookup
* manual entry
* missing hardware handling
* mandatory justification when bypassing return

Returned items are associated with the business request reference.

⸻

Delivery Workflow

After return handling:

* the new hardware delivery workflow is executed
* delivered items are added to the bucket

The technician may continue adding:

* additional hardware
* additional requests

⸻

6. Bucket Logic

Throughout the workflow:

* all delivered items
* all returned items

are progressively added into a common bucket.

The bucket represents the full transaction currently being processed.

This enables:

* consolidated review
* unified signature
* full traceability

⸻

7. Final Summary and Validation

At the end of the workflow, the system displays a complete delivery summary.

The technician can:

* review items
* modify information
* remove incorrect items if necessary

The user then:

* reviews the summary
* signs the delivery electronically

Finally, the technician:

* validates the operation
* saves traceability and history

The system then displays:

* post-delivery actions
* next operational steps if required

⸻

Key Functional Objectives

The workflow is designed to:

* Standardize hardware delivery operations
* Support onboarding and replacement scenarios
* Ensure complete hardware traceability
* Maintain technician flexibility in exceptional situations
* Preserve auditability when returns are bypassed
* Simplify operational workflows across all comptoirs
